  "answer": "**Ghalib — Diwan-e-Ghalib, chapter 231 [p-a37ab4]:**\n\n\"O Sāqī, even the stupor of unslaked thirst is measured by one's soul; / If you are a river of wine, I am the long, weary yawn of the shore.\"\n\n(Transliteration: ba-qadr-e-zarf hai saqi khumar-e-tishna-kaami bhi / jo tu darya-e-mai hai toh main khamyaza hoon sahil ka)\n\nThis is the heaviest saqi-couplet in the corpus for Ghalib. The saqi is not asked to pour wine at all — it is summoned to witness a metaphysical truth: even the intoxication produced by mere unslaked thirst (khumar-e-tishna-kaami) is bounded by the soul's own vessel (ba-qadr-e-zarf). If the saqi is an infinite river of wine, the poet is only the shore's exhausted yawn — passive, bounded, unable to absorb what the saqi would give. The saqi is asked to be a cosmic witness to the soul's fundamental capacity-limit. The transaction of the tavern collapses; what remains is an ontological reckoning. Beyond pouring: the saqi is asked to comprehend the incommensurability between divine generosity and the soul's finite vessel.\n\n---\n\n**Iqbal — Bang-e-Dara Part 3, chapter 20 (Shikwa) [p-bd43b7]:**\n\n\"We only live so that Your name may yet on earth remain; / Is it possible the cup-bearer is gone, but cups remain?\"\n\n(Transliteration: Hum to jeete hain ke duniya mein tera naam rahe / Kahin mumkin hai ke saaqi na rahe, jaam rahe!)\n\nThis is the heaviest saqi-couplet for Iqbal. The saqi here is not an individual wine-server — it is the living Muslim ummah itself, the community of devoted believers. The cups (jaam) are the empty religious forms: mosques, prayers, rituals still standing. The question is directed at God as a challenge: can You allow the cups to remain while the cup-bearer — the animating spiritual community — is gone? The saqi is implicitly summoned to remain present, to be the living spirit inside the hollow vessels of religion. Beyond pouring: the saqi is asked to be the soul of an entire civilization, to refuse the death that would leave cups without a cupbearer.\n\n---\n\n**Contrast:** Ghalib's saqi is confronted with a private, intimate metaphysical argument about the soul's bounded nature. Iqbal's saqi is addressed with a public, civilizational summons — to persist as the animating spirit of an entire religious community or render its forms meaningless.",
