**Summary of findings:**

**Ghalib (Diwan-e-Ghalib, ch. 231, p-a37ab4):**
> *"O Sāqī, even the stupor of unslaked thirst is measured by one's soul; / If you are a river of wine, I am the long, weary yawn of the shore."*

The saqi is asked not to pour wine but to *witness a metaphysical limit*: even the intoxication of mere longing (khumar-e-tishna-kaami) is bounded by the soul's vessel (ba-qadr-e-zarf). If the saqi is an infinite river, the poet is only the shore's yawn — unable to absorb what is offered. The saqi becomes a cosmic interlocutor confronted with the incommensurability between generosity and capacity.

**Iqbal (Bang-e-Dara Part 3, ch. 20 — Shikwa, p-bd43b7):**
> *"We only live so that Your name may yet on earth remain; / Is it possible the cup-bearer is gone, but cups remain?"*
> *(Kahin mumkin hai ke saaqi na rahe, jaam rahe!)*

The saqi here is the living Muslim ummah itself — the animating spirit. The cups are the empty religious forms. The question challenges God: can the vessels survive without the one who fills them? The saqi is summoned to be the soul of an entire civilization, not a dispensary of wine.

**Contrast:** Ghalib's saqi is confronted with a private ontological argument; Iqbal's saqi is given a civilizational summons.
